&lt;p&gt;The vampire squid (&lt;i&gt;Vampyroteuthis infernalis&lt;/i&gt;) has the &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.sciencealert.com/vampire-squid-from-hell-reveals-the-ancient-origins-of-octopuses&quot;&gt;largest cephalopod genome&lt;/a&gt; ever sequenced: more than 11 billion base pairs. That&amp;#8217;s more than twice as large as the biggest squid genomes.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It&amp;#8217;s technically not a squid: &amp;#8220;The vampire squid is a fascinating twig tenaciously hanging onto the cephalopod family tree. It&amp;#8217;s neither a squid nor an octopus (nor a vampire), but rather the last, lone remnant of an ancient lineage whose other members have long since vanished.&amp;#8221;&lt;/p&gt;
